Deltari measure — the Reed Law's quantification of flow, pressure, and throughput — translates into an unusual relationship with the Cutting Books' timing and measure theory. Where most Swordsman practitioners develop timing intuition through repetitive practice and internalized pattern recognition, a Deltari practitioner can approach timing as a measurable quantity subject to formal analysis — the interval between positions, the rate of approach, the pressure dynamics of a bind — in terms that their racial heritage provides native vocabulary for. In Midgaard's dueling court context, Deltari Swordsmen have produced formal analyses of timing windows that represent some of the most precise documentation of blade measure that the Registry's Cutting Books archive contains. The more practically significant advantage is in the Cutting Books' consistency requirement: Deltari measurement orientation produces practitioners who can identify when their own performance deviates from documented standard and diagnose the deviation's source, which makes self-correction more systematic.

