Kethari long-memory includes martial precedent that predates the Cutting Books corpus — older forms of documented blade practice from eras before the dueling court tradition formalized the Swordsman's theoretical framework. A Kethari practitioner who engages with the Cutting Books does so with awareness of what those Books refined out and what they refined in, which produces a specific form of theoretical depth: not just the Books' explicit principles but the history of why those principles replaced earlier approaches. In Kiess, where the anti-sealed-warrant archive preserves older documentation that other cities' repositories have lost, Kethari Swordsmen have access to pre-Cutting Books martial documentation that represents genuine theoretical alternatives to the standard canon. Wall Command assessors treat Kethari Swordsmen as unusually difficult to predict — their tactical decisions draw on precedent sets that opponents trained in standard Cutting Books doctrine have not studied, which is a specific advantage in the gap-exploitation function that frontier interdiction requires.
